# Executive Summary

NHS emergency departments across England have experienced growing operational pressure due to increasing patient demand, staffing shortages, and capacity constraints. Since 2013, the NHS has consistently failed to meet the national four-hour A&E target, with waiting times reaching record levels in recent years.

This project applies business analytics techniques to investigate the operational, demographic, and systemic factors contributing to prolonged waiting times within NHS England A&Es. Using publicly available NHS datasets between 2016 and 2023, the study combines regression analysis, correlation analysis, and Seasonal ARIMA (SARIMA) forecasting to identify the major contributors to delays and forecast future waiting time trends.

The analysis identified bed occupancy rates, workforce shortages, demographic disparities, and seasonal demand fluctuations as key contributors to prolonged waiting times. Forecasting analysis predicts that without intervention, over 800,000 patients per month may wait longer than four hours in A&E departments by 2027.

The project proposes data-driven management recommendations including dynamic resource allocation, predictive staffing models, AI-assisted patient prioritisation systems, and operational monitoring dashboards to improve patient flow and NHS operational efficiency.

